Test file: src/claim-office.spec.ts
Failing test: "should return 65 G for 3 runes (60 base, block applies + 5 fee)"
Expected behavior: 3 runes of the same type get a "block" discount: 60 G base instead of 3×25=75. Result = 60 + 5 = 65.
Current error: expected 80 to be 65 — no block logic exists
Implementation file: src/claim-office.ts

Current implementation:
```typescript
const PROCESSING_FEE = 5;

const BASE_PREMIUMS: Record<string, number> = {
  sword: 100,
  amulet: 60,
  staff: 80,
  potion: 40,
  rune: 25,
  moonstone: 25,
};

export function claimOffice(request: any): any {
  const items = request.steps[0].items;
  let basePremium = 0;
  for (const item of items) {
    basePremium += BASE_PREMIUMS[item.type];
  }
  return [{ premium: basePremium + PROCESSING_FEE }];
}
```

The block rule: components (rune, moonstone) can form a "building block" of exactly 3 alike components with a special base premium of 60 G instead of 3×25=75 G. "Alike" means same type. The block requires exactly 3 — 2 or 4 don't qualify.

Add minimal logic: count components by type. If exactly 3 of a component type, use 60 instead of 3×25. Otherwise use individual premiums. Keep it simple — just enough to pass this test AND the existing 2-rune test.

EXPERIMENT MODE: Run autonomously, proceed to Refactor after completion.

